Introduction

For my final project, I selected the 1987 National Indonesia Contraceptive Prevalence Survey dataset. This dataset was listed on UC Irvine’s Machine Learning Repository. There were no missing values or discrepancies however there is not a complete data dictionary. The dataset was sampled by surveying married women and their contraceptive method choice in Indonesia. The sample size is 1,473 respondents. There are ten variables that describe the woman’s age, education, religion, working status, contraceptive method, standard of living, media exposure as well as number of children and husband’s education and occupation. In this project, I observed the prediction of contraceptive methods based on the woman’s demographic and socioeconomic status.

Link to Github repository for code Here


Background

In 1987, fertility rates had rapidly fallen in Indonesia. On average, women were having 3.3 children versus 5.5 children two decades ago. The introduction of contraception use contributed to this drop of birth rates. Almost 95% of married women were familiar with contraceptive methods and were shifting their focus to structured family planning.

Variable Assessment

The distribution of wife’s age is not normal so I centralized it for easier interpretation (wife_age.c).

Wife’s Age and Number of Children are discrete variables. The rest are categorical or binary variables so I factored these variables. For easier analysis, I changed the factoring of contraceptive method so that short term (2) and long term (3) are in one category.


Var1 Freq
0 0.4270197
1 0.5729803

At a highlevel, in the sample 42% do not use contraceptive methods while 57% of woman do.


Table 2: Individual Relationships, Standard Errors, 95% CI, p-values

1. Wife Age vs Contraceptive

The graph shows a low then high then low pattern between wife’s age and contraception use. Near the mean of wife’s age, which is 32, woman are more likely to use contraception. The low and high end of the age ranges are showing no contraception use. There is a violation of linearity here.

Before modeling, I assessed the linearity of wife’s age using MFP.

MFP suggests I(wife_age.c2) + I(wife_age.c3) transformation.

Examining demographic confounding

The criteria for confounding is at least a 10% change in estimates and variables must be sensibly a cause to both X and Y.

I observed the interaction effect between wife’s age and number of children because of the correlation matrix. The interaction term is significant in the model. The model with the interaction is shown to have a lower AIC than the model with only selected predictors and no transformation (1738 vs 1792). I selected the model with the interaction as my final model.

Interpretation and Conclusion

A one unit increase in wife’s age is associated with 0.98 times the odds of contraceptive use. A one unit increase in number of children is associated with 1.61 times the odds of contraceptive use. A woman with higher education is associated with 4.28 times the odds than a woman with no education. A woman with a high standard of living index is associated with 2.1 times the odds than a woman with poor standard of living.

Overall, a woman’s age, education, religion, current number of children, standard of living, and media exposure can predict contraceptive use. From the diagnostics ran, the model can use improvement in terms of model fit but there is no influential data points.
